{"questionId":"28013","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The position vector of a particle at time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">j</mi></math>.&nbsp;Displacement is measured in metres and time is measured in seconds.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The position vector of a second particle is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">j</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>At time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>, where<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>, the second particle is moving parallel to the first particle.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>At time&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>, show that the two particles are moving in the opposite direction.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>30</mn></math>,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>22</mn><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">i</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>68</mn><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">j</mi></math>&nbsp; and&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>57</mn><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">j</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>22</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;(following second method in part (d)(i))&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a negative multiple of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>22</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>the two particles are moving in the opposite direction&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"28013","referenceCode":"22N.2.AHL.TZ0.7d.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"At tim